      ],
      "correctIndex": 1,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "\u26a0\ufe0f Common misconception! Specific heat capacity (c) is a property of the material \u2014 it tells you how much energy is needed to raise <strong>1 kg</strong> of that substance by <strong>1\u00b0C</strong>. It is not the total energy stored (that depends on mass and temperature change too).",
      "correctFeedback": "\u2713 Correct! Specific heat capacity is the energy needed per kilogram per degree Celsius. Water has a very high value (4200 J/kg\u00b0C) \u2014 it takes a lot of energy to heat up.",
      "bestSource": "BEST resource: AQA Physics specification 4.3.2 \u2014 Specific heat capacity"
